86. The partitive genitive in the singular or plural is occa- sionally dependent on an adjective in the neuter plural τ 12, 55 discriminis ultima ; 15, 95 bellorumque ultima ; cf. Lucr. 1, 1102 ultima naturai ; Luc. v111, 665 ultima mortis. This is rare in early Latin, but becomes common from the time of Livy, and is especially frequent in Tacitus.'

87. The genitive is used with felice to denote the seat of the feeling: 14, 119 animi felices. Such genitives (usually animi) may originally have been locatives.⁸
